"n./v. (猪等)在泥水中打滚；沉溺于 【英】 v./n.(猪等)在泥水中 打滚 (to roll about in mud)；沉溺于(to take unrestrained pleasure) 【记】 分割记忆：wall(墙)+ low(低下的) 【例】 wallow in the mire(在泥沼中打滚) v. /n. (在水里、雪中或泥浆中懒散地或笨拙地)打滚; 沉溺于 【记】wall(n 墙), low低: 导致水溢出－在水中打滚你的孩子要是wallow, 就wallop他. 【记】wall + low 矮墙，猪在矮墙内(猪圈)里打滚 wallow (v.)  Old English wealwian ""to roll,"" from West Germanic *walwon, from PIE root *wel- (3) ""to roll"" (see volvox). Figurative sense of ""to plunge and remain in some state or condition"" is attested from early 13c. Related: Wallowed; wallowing. The noun is recorded from 1590s as ""act of rolling;"" 1841 as ""place where an animal wallows."""
